React Component Lifecycle

The Component Lifecycle is the sequence of stages a component goes through from creation to removal.

There are 3 main phases:

1. Mounting   → Component is created and added to the DOM
2. Updating   → Component re-renders when state/props change
3. Unmounting → Component is removed from the DOM
1. Mounting Phase

When the component appears on the screen for the first time.

Functional Component
import { useEffect } from "react";

function App() {
  useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Component Mounted");
  }, []);

  return <h1>Hello</h1>;
}

Output:

Component Mounted

The empty dependency array [] means the effect runs only once after the first render.

2. Updating Phase

Occurs when:

State changes
Props change
import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

function App() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Component Updated");
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <>
      <h1>{count}</h1>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
        Increment
      </button>
    </>
  );
}

Every time count changes:

Component Updated

is printed.

3. Unmounting Phase

Occurs when a component is removed from the DOM.

import { useEffect } from "react";

function Child() {
  useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Mounted");

    return () => {
      console.log("Unmounted");
    };
  }, []);

  return <h2>Child Component</h2>;
}

The function returned from useEffect is called the cleanup function.

return () => {
  console.log("Unmounted");
};

It runs before the component is removed.

Complete Example
import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

function Child() {
  useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Mounted");

    return () => {
      console.log("Unmounted");
    };
  }, []);

  return <h2>Child Component</h2>;
}

function App() {
  const [show, setShow] = useState(true);

  return (
    <>
      <button onClick={() => setShow(!show)}>
        Toggle
      </button>

      {show && <Child />}
    </>
  );
}

export default App;

